Hi Yael, here is the sequel PR generalising "disjointed". As promised, it gets rid of the `Algebra/Order` dependencies in `Mathlib.Order.Disjointed` that were introduced in the previous PR.
Can you be consistent between `disjointed_succ` and `disjointed_add_one` on whether you take `[NoMaxOrder Î¹]` or `Â¬ IsMax i`?

That was a deliberate choice. The overwhelmingly most important use case of `disjointed_add_one` is when  `Î¹` is `â„•` or something order-isomorphic to it. I can't think of any interesting `SuccAddOrders` having a maximal element. But there certainly do exist `SuccOrder`s with a maximal element, such as `Fin n`. So making this consistent would either mean losing `Fin n`, or having to supply a tedious `Â¬ IsMax` side condition in every application to `â„•`, neither of which seems desirable.

```suggestion
lemma IsCaratheodory.biUnion_of_finite {Î¹ : Type*} {s : Î¹ â†’ Set Î±} {t : Set Î¹} (ht : t.Finite)
```

```suggestion
      .biUnion_of_finite m (finite_Iio _) fun j _ â†¦ h j
```
I think this porting note is irrelevant now?
